<node id="&quot;PHILADELPHIA CHROMOSOME&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Philadelphia chromosome is a specific chromosomal abnormality found in chronic myeloid leukemia (CML) patients."&lt;SEP&gt;"The Philadelphia chromosome is a genetic abnormality characterized by a translocation between chromosomes 9 and 22, which is a hallmark of chronic myeloid leukemia (CML)."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5a1c664c094403842e858c8931bde7c3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d0cf0b37864347226f145a22592586fb</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CHROMOSOME 9&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Chromosome 9 is a specific region of DNA that contains the c- _abl_ gene and is implicated in certain types of cancer."&lt;SEP&gt;"Chromosome 9 is one of the 23 pairs of human chromosomes where the c-ABL gene is normally located before translocation."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5a1c664c094403842e858c8931bde7c3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d0cf0b37864347226f145a22592586fb</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MOUSE ABELSON LEUKEMIA VIRUS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Mouse Abelson leukemia virus is a virus known to carry the v- _abl_ gene, which is associated with certain types of cancer."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d0cf0b37864347226f145a22592586fb</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CHRONIC MYELOID LEUKEMIA (CML)&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"DISEASE"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Chronic myeloid leukemia (CML) is a type of cancer characterized by an abnormal increase in white blood cells and is associated with the Philadelphia chromosome."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-d0cf0b37864347226f145a22592586fb</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;TRANSLOCATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Translocation is a genetic event where a segment of one chromosome breaks off and attaches to another chromosome, often seen in CML patients."&lt;SEP&gt;"Translocation refers to the movement of genetic material from one chromosome to another, which is a key characteristic of the Philadelphia chromosome in CML."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5a1c664c094403842e858c8931bde7c3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d0cf0b37864347226f145a22592586fb</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;DUTCH AND BRITISH RESEARCHERS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Dutch and British researchers are a team of scientists who conducted a study on the Philadelphia chromosome and discovered the translocation of the c-ABL gene."&lt;SEP&gt;"Dutch and British researchers are a team of scientists who conducted studies on the Philadelphia chromosome and the c- _abl_ gene."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5a1c664c094403842e858c8931bde7c3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d0cf0b37864347226f145a22592586fb</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;C-ABL GENE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GENE"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The c-ABL gene is a specific gene located on chromosome 9 that was found to have moved to chromosome 22 in patients with CML, forming a fusion gene with the bcr gene."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5a1c664c094403842e858c8931bde7c3</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CHROMOSOME 22&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Chromosome 22 is one of the 23 pairs of human chromosomes where the c-ABL gene was found to have moved after translocation."&lt;SEP&gt;"Chromosome 22 is one of the 23 pairs of human chromosomes where the c-ABL gene was found to have moved to after translocation."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5a1c664c094403842e858c8931bde7c3</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BCR GENE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GENE"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The bcr gene is a gene located on chromosome 22 that fuses with the c-ABL gene to form an abnormal protein in CML cells."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5a1c664c094403842e858c8931bde7c3</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CML CELLS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"CML cells are cancerous cells that exhibit the Philadelphia chromosome and the fusion of the c-ABL and bcr genes, leading to the production of an abnormal protein."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5a1c664c094403842e858c8931bde7c3</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PROTO-ONCOGENE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GENE"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A proto-oncogene is a normal gene that can potentially become an oncogene when mutated or expressed abnormally, leading to cancer."&lt;SEP&gt;"Proto-oncogene is a normal gene that can be transformed into an oncogene due to mutations or fusions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5a1c664c094403842e858c8931bde7c3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4808624bb772962b1d285e9a96aaec01</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ABNORMAL PROTEIN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"An abnormal protein is produced as a result of the fusion of the c-ABL and bcr genes, which is a hallmark of CML."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5a1c664c094403842e858c8931bde7c3</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;FIGURE 5.3&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"FIGURE"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Figure 5.3 illustrates the fusion of the bcr and abl genes and the resulting oncogene production."&lt;SEP&gt;"Figure 5.3 illustrates the translocation of the c-ABL gene to chromosome 22 and the fusion of the c-ABL and bcr genes."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5a1c664c094403842e858c8931bde7c3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4808624bb772962b1d285e9a96aaec01</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;C-ABL PROTEIN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"c-abl protein is a specific protein that has its 'head' fused to the 'tail' of the bcr protein in the context of producing an oncogene."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4808624bb772962b1d285e9a96aaec01</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 9}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 62}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BCR PROTEIN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"bcr protein is a specific protein that has its 'tail' fused to the 'head' of the c-abl protein in the context of producing an oncogene."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4808624bb772962b1d285e9a96aaec01</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 9}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 62}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ONCOGENE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Oncogene is a mutated form of a proto-oncogene that can lead to cancer."&lt;SEP&gt;"Oncogenes are genes that have the potential to cause cancer when mutated or expressed at high levels, with many oncogenes having the same general effect of disrupting cell regulation."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-6a1794c4fa3680656aaab5d3de43949e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4808624bb772962b1d285e9a96aaec01</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;TYROSINE KINASES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Tyrosine kinases are a class of enzymes that add phosphate groups to proteins, regulating their activities."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4808624bb772962b1d285e9a96aaec01</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PHOSPHATES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Phosphates are molecules that can be added or removed from proteins to regulate their activities."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4808624bb772962b1d285e9a96aaec01</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CELLULAR RELAY SYSTEMS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Cellular relay systems are pathways that transfer information from outside cells to internal cellular processes determining cell behavior."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4808624bb772962b1d285e9a96aaec01</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;C-ABL TYROSINE KINASE ACTIVITY&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"c-abl tyrosine kinase activity refers to the specific function of the c-abl protein in adding phosphate groups to proteins."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4808624bb772962b1d285e9a96aaec01</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BCR/ABL FUSION PROTEIN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"bcr/abl fusion protein is the result of the fusion of the c-abl protein's head and the bcr protein's tail, leading to elevated kinase activity."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4808624bb772962b1d285e9a96aaec01</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CHRONIC MYELOGENOUS LEUKEMIA CELLS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Chronic myelogenous leukemia cells are a type of cancer characterized by the presence of the bcr/abl fusion gene."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4808624bb772962b1d285e9a96aaec01</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;_ABL_ GENE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The _abl_ gene is located on chromosome 9 and is fused with the _bcr_ gene in myelogenous leukemia, producing a hybrid gene with abnormally elevated activity."&lt;SEP&gt;"_abl_ gene is a gene found on chromosome 9 that is part of the bcr/abl fusion gene in chronic myelogenous leukemia cells."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-6a1794c4fa3680656aaab5d3de43949e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4808624bb772962b1d285e9a96aaec01</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;_BCR_ GENE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The _bcr_ gene is located on chromosome 22 and fuses with the _abl_ gene in myelogenous leukemia, producing a hybrid gene with abnormally elevated activity."&lt;SEP&gt;"_bcr_ gene is a gene found on chromosome 22 that is part of the bcr/abl fusion gene in chronic myelogenous leukemia cells."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-6a1794c4fa3680656aaab5d3de43949e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4808624bb772962b1d285e9a96aaec01</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LEUK&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Leuk is a term used to refer to leukemia, a type of cancer involving blood cells."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4808624bb772962b1d285e9a96aaec01</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CONSTITUTIVE MUTANTS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Constitutive mutants are genetic variants that are always active, similar to the bcr/abl fusion protein."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-4808624bb772962b1d285e9a96aaec01</data>
