  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Figure 5.3 visually represents the translocation of the c-ABL gene to chromosome 22 and the fusion with the bcr gene."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-5a1c664c094403842e858c8931bde7c3</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;C-ABL GENE&quot;" target="&quot;CHROMOSOME 22&quot;">
  <data key="d4">20.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The c-ABL gene was found to have moved to chromosome 22 in patients with CML, forming a fusion gene with the bcr gene."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-5a1c664c094403842e858c8931bde7c3</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;C-ABL GENE&quot;" target="&quot;PROTO-ONCOGENE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">14.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The c-ABL gene is a proto-oncogene that becomes abnormal when it fuses with the bcr gene."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-5a1c664c094403842e858c8931bde7c3</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;CHROMOSOME 22&quot;" target="&quot;BCR GENE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">18.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The bcr gene is located on chromosome 22 and fuses with the c-ABL gene to form an abnormal protein in CML cells."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-5a1c664c094403842e858c8931bde7c3</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;PROTO-ONCOGENE&quot;" target="&quot;ONCOGENE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"A proto-oncogene can be transformed into an oncogene through fusions such as the bcr/abl fusion."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-4808624bb772962b1d285e9a96aaec01</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;ABNORMAL PROTEIN&quot;" target="&quot;FUSION GENE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">18.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The abnormal protein is produced as a result of the fusion of the c-ABL and bcr genes."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-5a1c664c094403842e858c8931bde7c3</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
